Task: How to open a JSON and append to it independently to whether it exists or not?

 <p>I am creating a program that implements a todo list using JSON as the storage system for persistency. However, the fisrt time running the program the file does not exist. Therefore, I would like to create a file and start apending to it if it does not exist, or open the existing file to append.</p>
<p>So far I've implemented a function that reads an existing file:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>fn load_file() -&gt; Vec&lt;String&gt; {
    let path = &quot;output.json&quot;;
    let data = fs::read_to_string(path).expect(&quot;Unable to read file.&quot;);
    serde_json::from_str(&amp;data).expect(&quot;Unable to parse file.&quot;)
}

fn main() {
    let file_contents = load_file();
}
</code></pre>
<p>This is different from <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/q/30684624/5397009">What is the best variant for appending a new line in a text file?</a> because the linked question appends at the very end of the file, but appending to a JSON file requires moving the closing <code>]</code> past the appended items.</p>


